'''Anutpada''' is a Buddhist concept for the absence of an origin. 

==Etymology==
"Anutpāda" means "having no origin", "not coming into existence", "not taking effect", "non-production".<ref>[http://spokensanskrit.de/index.php?script=HK&beginning=0+&tinput=anutpAda+&trans=Translate&direction=AU Sanskrit Dictionary for Spoken Sanskrit, ''Anutpāda'']</ref>
* "An" also means "not", or "non"
* "Utpāda" means "genesis", "coming forth", "birth"<ref>[http://spokensanskrit.de/index.php?tinput=utpAda&script=&direction=SE&link=yes Sanskrit Dictionary for Spoken Sanskrit, ''Utpāda'']</ref>

==Usage in Buddhist tradition==
The Buddhist tradition uses the term "anutpāda" for the absence of an origin{{sfn|Renard|2010|p=157}}{{sfn|Bhattacharya|1943|p=49}} or [[sunyata]] (voidness).{{sfn|Renard|2010|p=160}} ''Anutpāda'' means that ''[[dharma]]s'', the constituting elements of reality, do not come into existence.{{sfn|King|1995|p=113}} [[Atiśa]]:
{{quote|One may wonder, "From where did all this come in the first place, and to where does it depart now?" Once examined in this way, [one sees that] it neither comes from anywhere nor departs to anywhere. All inner and outer phenomena are [[Tathatā|just like that]].{{sfn|Brunholzl|2004|p=295}}{{refn|group=note|Brunholzl quotes Atisha's ''Centrist Pith Instructions, Called The Open jewel Casket''.}}{{refn|group=note|Compare the [[Upanishads]], for example the [[Mundaka Upanishad]], where the same question is being asked, but where the answer is that [[Brahman]] is the origin of All.}}}}

[[Chandrakirti]], in his ''Yuktisastikavrrti'', states:
{{quote|Nagarjuna taught, "bereft of beginning, middle, and end," meaning that the world is free from creation, duration, and destruction.<ref>Loizzo, Joesph ''Nagarjuna's Reason Sixty.'' American Institute of Buddhist Studies 2007, page 177.</ref>}}

According to Nakamura in his study of Advaita  Vedanta, the Buddhist ''[[Paramārtha-satya|paramārtha]]'', "highest truth", is identified with ''anutpāda'' {{sfn|Nakamura|2004|p=255}} The term ''paramārtha'' is a synonym for [[tattva]], [[tathata]], [[sunyata]], [[Bhūmi (Buddhism)#The sixth bhūmi, the Manifest|animitta]], [[Buddha-nature#Vajrasamadhi-sutra (685 CE)|bhutakoti]] and [[dharmadhatu]].{{sfn|Nakamura|2004|p=255}} One who understands sunyata, anutpada and dependent arising, has realized the ultimate truth and gains nirvana. Nagarjuna:
{{quote|[67] Nothing exists by virtue of own-being, nor is there any non-being here. Being and non-being, born through causes and conditions, are empty.<br>
[68] Since all things are empty of own-being, the incomparable Tathagata teaches dependent co-origination regarding things.<br>
[69] The ultimate meaning consists in that! The perfect Buddhas, the Bhagavats, have [only] conceived the entire multiplicity in reliance upon worldly convention.<br>
[70] The worldly norms [dharmas] are not violated. In reality [the Tathagata] has not taught the Dharma. Not understanding the Tathagata's words, [fools] fear this spotless discourse.<br>
[71] The worldly principle, "This arises depending on that," is not violated. But since what is dependent lacks own-being, how can it exist? That is certain!<br>
[72] One with faith who tries to seek the truth, one who considers this principle logically [and] relies [upon] the Dharma that is lacking all supports leaves behind existence and non-existence [and abides in] peace.<br>
[73] When one understands that "This is a result of that/' the nets of bad views all vanish. Undefiled, one abandons desire, delusion, and hatred and gains nirvana.<ref name="Seventy">[http://www.purifymind.com/Sutras5.htm Nagarjuna, ''Sunyatasaptati. Seventy Verses on Sunyata.'']</ref>}}

''Anutpāda'' is one of the important features of the [[Prajnaparamita|Prajñāpāramitā Sutras]] and [[Madhyamaka]].{{refn|group=note|Buswell, Robert; Lopez, Donald S. Jr., eds. (2014), ''The Princeton Dictionary of Buddhism'', Princeton University Press pg. 945   "In the PRAJÑĀPĀRAMITĀ  literature  and  the MADHYAMAKA  school,  the  notion  of production  comes  under  specific criticism  (see VAJRAKAṆĀ),  with NĀGĀRJUNA  famously  asking,  e.g.,  how an  effect can be produced  from  a  cause that  is  either  the  same  as  or  different from  itself.  The  prajñāpāramitā  sūtras thus  famously declare  that  all  dharmas are  actually ANUTPĀDA,  or “unproduced.”"}}{{refn|group=note|King, Richard (1995), ''Early Advaita Vedānta and Buddhism: The Mahāyāna Context of the Gauḍapādīya-kārikā'', SUNY Press pg.113 "It is equally apparent that one of the important features of the Prajnaparamita positition is that of the nonarising (anutpada) of dharmas."}} The term is also being used in the [[Lankavatara Sutra]].{{sfn|Suzuki|1999}} According to D.T Suzuki, "anutpada" is not the opposite of "utpada", but transcends opposites. It is the [[Kensho|seeing into the true nature of existence]],{{sfn|Suzuki|1999|p=123-124}} the seeing that "all objects are [[Sunyata|without self-substance]]".{{sfn|Suzuki|1999|p=168}} Another well-known use is in [[Bankei Yōtaku|Bankei's]] "Unborn".{{sfn|Dumoulin|2005|p=316}}

==Influence on Gaudapada==
{{Main|Advaita Vedanta|Ajativada}}

Gaudapada-karika characterizes Brahman-Atman Absolute with the concept of "Ajātivāda". It is a fundamental philosophical doctrine of [[Gaudapada]].{{sfn|Sarma|1996|p=127}} In ''Gaudapada-Karika'', chapter III, verses 46-48, Gaudapada states that [[Brahman]] never arises, is never born, is never unborn, it rests in itself:
{{quote|
When the mind does not lie low, and is not again tossed about, then that being without movement, and not presenting any appearance, culminates into [[Brahman]]. Resting in itself, calm, with Nirvana, indescribable, highest happiness, unborn and one with the unborn knowable, omniscient they say. No creature whatever is born, no origination of it exists or takes place. This is that highest truth where nothing whatever is born.
|Gaudapada Karika|3.46-48, Translated by RD Karmarkar<ref>RD Karmarkar, [https://archive.org/stream/Gaudapada-Karika.English/Gaudapada-Karika#page/n83/mode/2up Gaudapada's Karika], Bhandarkar Oriental Research Institute</ref>}}

According to Gaudapada, the Absolute has no origin, and is not subject to [[Saṃsāra|birth, change and death]]. The Absolute is ''aja'', the unborn eternal.{{sfn|Sarma|1996|p=127}} The [[Empiricism|empirical world]] of [[phenomenon|appearances]] is considered [[Maya (illusion)|Maya]] (unreal, changing, transitory), and not [[Philosophical realism|ontologically independent reality]].{{sfn|Sarma|1996|p=127}}

Gaudapada's concept of "ajāta" is similar to Nagajurna's  Madhyamaka philosophy.{{sfn|Renard|2010|p=157}}{{sfn|Comans|2000|p=35-36}} The Buddhist tradition usually uses the term "anutpāda" for the absence of an origin{{sfn|Renard|2010|p=157}}{{sfn|Bhattacharya|1943|p=49}} or śūnyatā.{{sfn|Renard|2010|p=160}}

But Gaudapada's perspective is quite different from Nagarjuna.{{sfn|Comans|2000|p=36}} Gaudapada's perspective is based on the ''[[Mandukya Upanishad]]''.{{sfn|Comans|2000|p=36}} According to Gaudapada, Brahman cannot undergo alteration, so the phenomenal world cannot arise independently from Brahman. If the world cannot arise, yet is an empirical fact, than the world has to be an unreal (transitory) appearance of Brahman. And if the phenomenal world is a transitory appearance, then there is no real origination or destruction, only apparent origination or destruction. From the level of ultimate truth (''paramārthatā'') the phenomenal world is ''[[Maya (illusion)|māyā]]'',{{sfn|Comans|2000|p=36}}{{sfn|Hiriyanna|2000|p=25, 160-161}} changing and not what it seems to be.<ref>M Hiriyanna (2000), The Essentials of Indian Philosophy, Motilal Banarsidass, {{ISBN|978-8120813304}}, pages 25, 160-161</ref><ref>Wendy Doniger O'Flaherty (1986), Dreams, Illusion, and Other Realities, University of Chicago Press, {{ISBN|978-0226618555}}, page 119</ref>

The Ajativada of Gaudapada, states Karmarkar, has nothing in common with the Sunyavada concept in Buddhism.<ref>RD Karmarkar, [https://archive.org/stream/Gaudapada-Karika.English/Gaudapada-Karika#page/n45/mode/2up/search/ajativada Gaudapada's Karika], Bhandarkar Oriental Research Institute, pages xxxix-xl</ref> While the language of Gaudapada is undeniably similar to those found in Mahayana Buddhism, Coman states that their perspective is different because unlike Buddhism, Gaudapada is relying on the premise of "Brahman, [[Atman (Hinduism)|Atman]] or Turiya" exist and are the nature of absolute reality.{{sfn|Comans|2000|p=36}}{{Clarify|date=May 2017}}

